people.name: Christian  Selch
people.notes: Immigrated with wife Wilhelmine from Russia in 1892. bringing August, Paulina, Mary, Theophilia; settling first in Winnipeg. In 1896 August Selch took a homestead on 16-13-8E in Green Bay, MB. Christian settled with them. The homestead was a dense forest. With the help of a team of oxen they began to clear the land. Soon they also acquired a horse. The horse, teamed up with the one owned by the neighbouring Litke family enabled the 2 families to make trips to Beausejour for supplies. German records show Selch name also Salcher, Selchert

people.name: Julius George DeMarco

people.name: Vilhelm (Bill)  Selch
people.notes: Vilhelm took over the Green Bay homestead when he married Alvine Litke on 06/13/1922 at Zion Lutheran Church, Beausejour by Pastor Buechner. Both were active in the church all their lives, singing in the choir starting at the ages of 16 and 14 respectively. Vilhelm was a church councillor for 7 years and choir director from 1965 to 1980 when daughter Lily took over. They were engaged in mixed farming and for many years Vilhelm operated a threshing machine for his father and did custom threshing for the neighbours well into November. Vilhelm also worked for the RM of Brokenhead as an operator of a pull-type road grader and later he operated a well-drilling machine with his brother-in-law Emil Litke. He recalled those winters when he used to pick up cream in cans from farmers in Green Bay. He then hauled them to the Beausejour Creamery. For this purpose a horse-drawn heated caboose, mounted on a sleigh, was used. In 1945 Vilhelm went to the bush and hauled out logs and made lumber for the home he built in 1946. Vilhelm and Alvina officially retired from farming in 1977.

people.name: Evangeline (Van  Selch
people.notes: Married Martin Okalita 06/24/1961 in St. Paul's Lutheran Church Green Bay by Reverend Green of Lac du Bonnet. Green Bay was temporarily without a minister. Their first home was the Green Bay teacherage where Vangie taught grades 1-4. Martin taught high school in Beausejour. In 1962 they moved to Beausejour where they built their first home. Vangie taught greades 1-3 in Garson from 1964-66. In 1966 they sold their home and built another in Lac du Bonnet where Martin was principal in the Lac du Bonnet Senior School. Vangie taught grade 2 in Lac du Bonnet Elementary School from 1968-69. Martin was principal from 1966-1978 when he was transferred to Beausejour Senior School. In 1977 Vangie and Martin took over the farm from Vangie's parents. They started building a home and in 1978 they moved to live on the farm. Martin has continued teaching in Beausejour and has rented the land to their neighbours Pat and Larry Johnson. They are members of St. Paul's Lutheran Church in Green Bay and are members of the choir.

people.name: August  Selch
people.notes: Was one of the founders of St. Paul's Lutheran Church in Green Bay, MB 1898. Married Amalia Weise 04/20/1900 who arrived from Europe. They met and were married in Winnipeg by Pastor F. Beer. In 1917 they moved to a farm on the east side of Beausejour, but the Green Bay property was kept for grain. They started a dairy business in 1928. Initially all the cows were milked by hand, and the milk, in 8 gallon cans had to be hauled by horse-drawn wagon to the railway station in Beausejour, to be shipped to Winnipeg. By 1935 the milk was picked up by a transfer truck and hauled to the city. August Selch was the first to own a cream separator.

people.name: August (Art) Arthur Selch
people.notes:
In 1945 Arthur and wife Dorothy took over the dairy from August Selch. In 1948 they started using a milking machine powered by a gasoline motor. In 1952 when electric power became available the machine was converted to an electric unit. August Arthur sold the dairy herd in 1963.
Sept 1 2002 - whilst visiting Beausejour Cemetery, Dave Hagborg was pushing Art in a wheelchair. The ground was rough and the chair almost upset. Art said 'Hey, Dave, you have to dig the hole first before you throw me out!"
